Array Questions (In-Place)

Reverse an array

Input: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

Output: [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]

Approach: Use two pointers (i=0, j=n-1) and swap elements until i<j.

Find duplicate in an array (1 to n)

Input: [3, 1, 3, 4, 2]

Output: 3

Approach: Use index marking (negate the value at index abs(arr[i]) - 1). If already negative, that number is duplicate.

Remove duplicates from sorted array

Input: [1,1,2,2,3,4,4]

Output: [1,2,3,4] (in-place, return new length)

Approach: Two pointer method (slow and fast).

Move zeros to the end

Input: [0,1,0,3,12]

Output: [1,3,12,0,0]

Approach: Use two pointers to shift non-zero elements forward.

Find missing number (1 to n)

Input: [3,0,1]

Output: 2

Approach: Use XOR or sum formula (n*(n+1))/2.

Rotate array by k

Input: [1,2,3,4,5,6,7], k=3

Output: [5,6,7,1,2,3,4]

Approach: Reverse full array, then reverse first k and last n-k.

Check if array is sorted and rotated

Input: [3,4,5,1,2]

Output: true

Approach: Count number of "drops" (where arr[i] > arr[i+1]). If more than 1, return false.

üîπ Map / Frequency-Based Questions (But without extra DS)

Since you can‚Äôt use HashMap, here are tricks:

Find frequency of elements (range: 1 to n only)

Modify array by using index as a counter:

arr[arr[i] % n] += n;


Finally, arr[i]/n gives frequency.

Find majority element (> n/2 times)

Use Moore‚Äôs Voting Algorithm (O(1) space).

Check if two arrays are equal (without HashMap)

Sort both arrays and compare element by element.

Find first repeating element

Use index marking (negating like in duplicate detection).

Find missing and repeating element (1 to n)

Use XOR or math formula (sum of n natural numbers ‚Äì actual sum) and (sum of squares) to derive missing and repeating.

‚úÖ These questions are basic but cover array + map logic.
‚úÖ All are in-place, without extra space.
‚úÖ Common in FAANG-style DSA interviews for freshers/juniors.

